    {
      "url": "https://cdn.misoenergy.org/2022-06-01_MISO%20Comments_AD21-15-000624999.pdf",
      "title": "[PDF] united states of america",
      "published_date": "2022-06-01T00:00:00.000Z",
      "text": "UNITED STATES OF AMERICA FEDERAL ENERGY REGULATORY COMMISSION\n\nJoint Federal Task Force on ) Electric Transmission ) Docket No. AD21-15-000\n\nCOMMENTS OF THE MIDCONTINENT INDEPENDENT SYSTEM OPERATOR, INC.\n\nMISO appreciates the opportunity to provide comments in this proceeding and assist the\n\nJoint Federal Task Force on Electric Transmission (“Task Force”) in its efforts. The Task Force can play a critical role in working with states in each Order 1000 planning region to identify the unique needs and challenges of each region, and as a result, help to develop appropriate regional solutions to best address those needs both on an interconnection and planning basis. 1\n\nINTRODUCTION\n\nAlthough the current pro forma interconnection agreements and processes have not kept up with the challenges presented by a changing resource mix, and some regions may have failed to make progress on interconnection reforms, MISO has engaged in numerous efforts to improve processing time and efficiency of the interconnection process over the last several years. In addition, MISO’s robust, futures-based planning process has enabled MISO to move forward a significant tranche of projects through our Long Range Transmission Plan (“LRTP”). As discussed further below, this large build out will further enable the grid of the future to efficiently and reliably support the resource transition currently underway.\n\nMISO was among the first regions to see the impacts of the change in resource development from traditional dispatchable resources such as gas and coal fired units to intermittent resources\n\n1 MISO identified the work that this Task Force is conducting as an important effort in addressing the issues raised in the Advanced Notice of Proposed Rulemaking. Comments of the Midcontinent Indep. Sys. Operator, Inc., Building for the Future Through Electric Regional Transmission Planning and Cost Allocation and Generator Interconnection, Docket No. RM21-17-000, (October 12, 2021) (“ANOPR”) at 33.\n\nsuch as wind generation that sought to take advantage of wind-rich areas in the MISO footprint.\n\nMISO has been working consistently to improve the interconnection processes and transmission planning to meet the emerging challenges. As a result, MISO has the foundational planning practices, interconnection processes and cost allocation collaboration in place to support the region’s robust evolution. While more work will be done, MISO stands ready to help share its experiences and observations to the Task Force, and note that any proposed action or reforms should not “pull back” the successes of regions such as MISO that have moved forward on multiple fronts with improvements vetted through robust stakeholder processes.\n\nTopic 1: Generator Interconnection Queue Processes and Current Backlog\n\nOver the past several years, MISO has continuously worked with stakeholders to improve the generator interconnection queue by engaging in several major queue reform efforts. MISO’s interconnection and planning processes work together to ensure that the region’s infrastructure is developed in an efficient manner that allows an equitable allocation of costs across beneficiaries.\n\nMISO comprehensively restructured its Generator Interconnection Procedures (“GIP”) 2 in\n\n2017 by instituting a three-phase Definitive Planning Phase (“DPP”), 3 which includes sequential\n\nSystem Impact Studies (“SIS”), a separate financial milestone at the beginning of each DPP phase, 4 and two “off-ramps” 5 to allow interconnection customers with generator interconnection (“GI”)\n\nprojects that are no longer viable to exit the queue with minimal impacts on other GI projects. 6\n\n2 The GIP is the Generator Interconnection Procedures located in MISO’s Tariff as Attachment X. \n3 The DPP is MISO’s generator interconnection study process, during which MISO performs clustered \ninterconnection studies for specific geographically-organized groups of interconnection requests. MISO conducts \nreliability and deliverability studies that determine whether there is available transmission capacity to \naccommodate the interconnection of a new, proposed generating facility or whether network upgrades are needed. \n4 There are three financial milestones under the GIP: M2, M3, and M4. M2 marks the beginning of DPP Phase I, \nM3 marks the beginning of DPP Phase II, and M4 marks the beginning of DPP Phase III. \n5 These off-ramps are known as Interconnection Customer Decision Points I and II (“Decision Points I and II”). \nTariff, Attachment X, Section 7.3.1.4 & Section 7.3.2.4. \n6 See Filing of Revisions to the Open Access Transmission, Energy and Operating Reserve Markets Tariff to \nReform MISO’s Generator Interconnection Procedures, Docket No. ER17-156-000 (Oct. 21, 2016) (“2017 Queue \n\nFollowing the implementation of the 2017 Queue Reform, MISO and its stakeholders continued to evaluate the effectiveness of the revised GIP, responding to emerging issues and refining the initial design with various improvements, both internally and through FERC filings. 7 During those successive GIP enhancement efforts, MISO strengthened its site control and milestone rules, improved affected system study coordination with its RTO neighbors, responded to Commission rulemakings involving generator interconnections such as Order No. 845, and implemented many other improvements to the GIP and related processes. MISO provided an overview of these improvements to the Task Force. That presentation is provided as an appendix to this filing.\n\nIn the last several years, MISO has continued its efforts to improve the GIP. We closed a loophole in the GIA, 8 further improved the Site Control deadline, 9 clarified surplus interconnection, 10 implemented an automated pre-queue application process, 11 and established a means by which existing generation may be replaced without needing to complete the interconnection queue. 12 MISO is committed to making future improvements independent of any new rule requirements, and are intended to address the MISO system needs while also\n\nreflecting the input of our stakeholders.\n\nReform”). The 2017 Queue Reform became effective on January 4, 2017. See Midcontinent Indep. Sys. Operator, Inc., 158 FERC ¶ 61,003 (“2017 Queue Reform Order”), order on reh’g, 161 FERC ¶ 61,137 (2017) (“2017 Queue Reform Rehearing Order”). 7 See, e.g., Midcontinent Indep. Sys. Operator, Inc., 163 FERC ¶ 61,021 (2018) (order accepting changes to the deadline for Interconnection Customers to revise their Network Resource Interconnection Service election); Midcontinent Indep. Sys. Operator, Inc., 164 FERC ¶ 61,234 (2018) (order accepting changes to the scope of studies performed in DPP Phase I); Letter Order, Revisions to Appendix 1 of Attachment X, FERC Docket Nos. ER19-1103-000, ER19-1103-001 (April 23, 2019) (order accepting changes to improve the processing of hybrid generating facility proposals). 8 Letter Order, Proposed Revisions to MISO Tariff to Close the Post GIA Termination Loophole, Docket No. ER21-525-000 (January 28, 2021). 9 Letter Order, Revisions to Site Control Deadline, Docket No. ER21-1964-000 (June 24, 2021). 10 Letter Order, Surplus Interconnection Service, Docket No. ER21-351-000 (December 22, 2020). 11 Letter Order, Revisions to Attachment X and Attachment X, Appendix 1, Docket No. ER20-1211-000 (April 17, 2020). 12 Midcontinent Indep. Sys. Operator, Inc., 167 FERC ¶ 61,146 (2019).\n\nMISO is pleased to report that its interconnection queue is trending in the right direction.\n\nWhile there are improvements that can be made, MISO now is beginning to reap the rewards of its numerous reforms. We expect continued improvements in the state of queue as these reforms take further hold and new reforms take effect. For example, in the next year, MISO anticipates an increase in the speed to complete a DPP Cycle. MISO completed the DPP 2018 Cycle in 932 days and the DPP 2019 Cycle is scheduled to be completed in 953 days. MISO is anticipating that it will be able to ",
