      "text": "Madison Pitts Associate Corporate Counsel Direct Dial: 317-316-7911 Email: mpitts@misoenergy.org\n\nJanuary 30, 2024\n\nVIA ELECTRONIC FILING\n\nDebbie-Anne Reese \nSecretary \nFederal Energy Regulatory Commission \n888 First Street, N.E \nWashington, D.C. 20246 \n\nRe: Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. Docket No. ER24-_____-000 Generator Replacement Improvement Revisions\n\nDear Secretary Reese:\n\nThe Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (“MISO”) hereby submits 1proposed revisions to Attachment X—Generator Interconnection Procedures (“Attachment X”) and Module C—Energy and Operating Reserve Markets (“Module C”) of its Open Access Transmission Tariff (“Tariff”). The purpose of the revisions is to streamline MISO’s current generator replacement process and clarify certain other requirements. As part of these improvements, MISO proposes to align the study requirements found in its Attachment X with the requirements in Attachment Y Notification of Potential Resource (“Attachment Y”) for replacement requests, mitigate unnecessary study submission lead times for duplicative study requirements, and clarify the application of the one-year replacement submission requirement for facilities with an approved suspension request. These proposed revisions do not substantively change or expand the generator replacement process as accepted by the Commission. 2 MISO requests that the proposed revisions be made effective as of March 31, 2024, which is at least sixty (60) days after filing.\n\nI. BACKGROUND\n\nA. DEVELOPMENT OF THE GENERATOR REPLACEMENT PROCESS\n\nBefore the advent of generator replacement, owners of generating facilities had to use two separate procedures to convert an existing generating facility to a more efficient technology. First, the generator had to follow the procedure for the suspension or retirement of the existing generating facility under Section 38.2.7(a) of Module C and Attachment Y of the Tariff. This\n\n1 MISO makes this filing pursuant to section 205 of the Federal Power Act (“FPA”), 16 U.S.C. § 824d, and Part \n35 of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission’s (“FERC” or “Commission”) regulations, 18 C.F.R. § 35.0 \net seq. (2022). All capitalized terms in this filing that are not otherwise defined have the same meaning as they \nhave under the current MISO Tariff. \n2 Midcontinent Indep. Sys. Operator, Inc., 167 FERC ¶ 61,146 (“May 2019 Order”). \nSecretary Debbie-Anne Reese \nJanuary 30, 2024 \nPage 2 \n\n| process required the owner of the existing generating facility to submit a notice of the planned | | |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| retirement to MISO at least 26 weeks prior to the resource's retirement effective date (“Attachment | | |\n| Y Notice”). | During the Attachment Y Notice period, MISO would conduct a study to determine | |\n| whether all or a portion of the resource's capacity is necessary to maintain system reliability. | | If |\n| the resource’s capacity was necessary, it was designated as a | | System Support Resource (“SSR |\n| Unit”). If MISO could not maintain system reliability prior to the retirement effective date, then | | |\n| MISO required the SSR Unit to continue to operate, as needed, and MISO would compensate the | | |\n| resource owner accordingly. After the resource owner completed this process, the resource owner | | |\n| then had to submit a new interconnection request to MISO for the generating facility that would | | |\n| replace the existing generating facility. | | The replacement generating facility would be required to |\n| follow the full set of interconnection procedures under Attachment X in MISO's Tariff, which | | |\n| includes the Definitive Planning Phase (“DPP”). | | 6 Under this regime, the resource owner had no |\n| guarantee that it could retire the existing generating facility at the time proposed in the Attachment | | |\n| Y Notice. | This “dual track” retire and then replace process created numerous inefficiencies for | |